threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, missing section headers at jd

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a variation of the 'BillGates' (also known as Elknot) malware family, a persistent Linux botnet used for DDoS attacks and as a backdoor. It demonstrates classic malicious behaviors including multi-stage persistence by creating SysV init scripts in '/etc/init.d/' and modifying '/etc/crontab' to execute a script at '/etc/cron.hourly/gcc.sh' every three minutes. It performs process enumeration via '/proc' and network monitoring via '/proc/net/tcp'. The binary contains hardcoded HTTP request templates for C2 communication and is capable of downloading additional payloads to '/tmp/'. It also features routines to interact with '/proc/rs_dev', a path frequently associated with rootkit-level kernel modules for hiding malicious activity.
